# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: cancer-genome-sequencing
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/454-life-sciences] 454 Life Sciences was founded by Jonathan Rothberg and was originally known as 454 Corporation, a subsidiary of CuraGen.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/454-life-sciences] For their method for low-cost gene sequencing, 454 Life Sciences was awarded the Wall Street Journal's Gold Medal for Innovation in the Biotech-Medical category in 2005.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/454-life-sciences] The name 454 was the code name by which the project was referred to at CuraGen, and the numbers have no known special meaning.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/454-life-sciences] In November 2006, Rothberg, Michael Egholm, and colleagues at 454 published a cover article with Svante Pääbo in Nature describing the first million base pairs of the Neanderthal genome, and initiated the Neanderthal Genome Project to complete the sequence of the Neanderthal genome by 2009.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/454-life-sciences] In late March 2007, Roche Diagnostics acquired 454 Life Sciences for US$154.9 million.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/454-life-sciences] In October 2013, Roche announced that it would shut down 454, and stop supporting the platform by mid-2016.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/454-life-sciences] In May 2007, 454 published the results of Project "Jim": the sequencing of the genome of James Watson, co-discoverer of the structure of DNA.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/454-life-sciences] 454 Sequencing used a large-scale parallel pyrosequencing system capable of sequencing roughly 400-600 megabases of DNA per 10-hour run on the Genome Sequencer FLX with GS FLX Titanium series reagents.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/454-life-sciences] The system relied on fixing nebulized and adapter-ligated DNA fragments to small DNA-capture beads in a water-in-oil emulsion.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/454-life-sciences] The DNA fixed to these beads was then amplified by PCR.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/454-life-sciences] Each DNA-bound bead was placed into a ~29 μm well on a PicoTiterPlate, a fiber optic chip.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/454-life-sciences] A mix of enzymes such as DNA polymerase, ATP sulfurylase, and luciferase was also packed into the well.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/454-life-sciences] The PicoTiterPlate was then placed into the GS FLX System for sequencing.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/454-life-sciences] 454 released the GS20 sequencing machine in 2005, the first next-generation DNA sequencer on the market.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/454-life-sciences] In 2008, 454 Sequencing launched the GS FLX Titanium series reagents for use on the Genome Sequencer FLX instrument, with the ability to sequence 400-600 million base pairs per run with 400-500 base pair read lengths.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/454-life-sciences] In late 2009, 454 Life Sciences introduced the GS Junior System, a bench top version of the Genome Sequencer FLX System.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/454-life-sciences] Genomic DNA was fractionated into smaller fragments (300-800 base pairs) and polished (made blunt at each end).
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/454-life-sciences] Short adaptors were then ligated onto the ends of the fragments.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/454-life-sciences] These adaptors provided priming sequences for both amplification and sequencing of the sample-library fragments.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/454-life-sciences] One adaptor (Adaptor B) contained a 5'-biotin tag for immobilization of the DNA library onto streptavidin-coated beads.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/454-life-sciences] After nick repair, the non-biotinylated strand was released and used as a single-stranded template DNA (sstDNA) library.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/454-life-sciences] The sstDNA library was assessed for its quality, and the optimal amount (DNA copies per bead) needed for emPCR is determined by titration.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/454-life-sciences] The sstDNA library was immobilized onto beads.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/454-life-sciences] The beads containing a library fragment carried a single sstDNA molecule.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/454-life-sciences] The bead-bound library was emulsified with the amplification reagents in a water-in-oil mixture.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/454-life-sciences] Each bead was captured within its own microreactor where PCR amplification occurs.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/454-life-sciences] This resulted in bead-immobilized, clonally amplified DNA fragments.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/454-life-sciences] Single-stranded template DNA library beads were added to the DNA Bead Incubation Mix (containing DNA polymerase) and were layered with *Enzyme Beads* (containing sulfurylase and luciferase) onto a PicoTiterPlate device.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/454-life-sciences] The device was centrifuged to deposit the beads into the wells.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/454-life-sciences] The layer of Enzyme Beads ensured that the DNA beads remained positioned in the wells during the sequencing reaction.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/454-life-sciences] The bead-deposition process was designed to maximize the number of wells that contain a single amplified library bead.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/454-life-sciences] The loaded PicoTiterPlate device were placed into the Genome Sequencer FLX Instrument.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/454-life-sciences] The fluidics sub-system delivered sequencing reagents (containing buffers and nucleotides) across the wells of the plate.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/454-life-sciences] The four DNA nucleotides were added sequentially in a fixed order across the PicoTiterPlate device during a sequencing run.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/454-life-sciences] During the nucleotide flow, millions of copies of DNA bound to each of the beads were sequenced in parallel.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/454-life-sciences] When a nucleotide complementary to the template strand was added into a well, the polymerase extended the existing DNA strand by adding nucleotide(s).
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/454-life-sciences] Addition of one (or more) nucleotide(s) generated a light signal that was recorded by the CCD camera in the instrument.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/454-life-sciences] This technique was based on sequencing-by-synthesis and called pyrosequencing.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/454-life-sciences] The signal strength was proportional to the number of nucleotides; for example, homopolymer stretches, incorporated in a single nucleotide flow, generated a greater signal than single nucleotides.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/454-life-sciences] However, the signal strength for homopolymer stretches was linear only up to eight consecutive nucleotides, after which the signal fell off rapidly.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/454-life-sciences] Data were stored in standard flowgram format (SFF) files for downstream analysis.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/abi-solid-sequencing] These methods have reduced the cost from $0.01/base in 2004 to nearly $0.0001/base in 2006 and increased the sequencing capacity from 1,000,000 bases/machine/day in 2004 to more than 5,000,000,000 bases/machine/day in 2009.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/abi-solid-sequencing] Over 30 publications exist describing its use first for nucleosome positioning from Valouev et al., transcriptional profiling or strand sensitive RNA-Seq with Cloonan et al., single cell transcriptional profiling with Tang et al. and ultimately human resequencing with McKernan et al.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/abi-solid-sequencing] The method used by this machine (sequencing-by-ligation) has been reported to have some issue sequencing palindromic sequences.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/abi-solid-sequencing] A library of DNA fragments is prepared from the sample to be sequenced, and is used to prepare clonal bead populations.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/abi-solid-sequencing] That is, only one species of fragment will be present on the surface of each magnetic bead.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/abi-solid-sequencing] The fragments attached to the magnetic beads will have a universal P1 adapter sequence attached so that the starting sequence of every fragment is both known and identical.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/abi-solid-sequencing] Emulsion PCR takes place in microreactors containing all the necessary reagents for PCR.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/abi-solid-sequencing] The beads with the resulting PCR products are deposited to a glass slide.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/abi-solid-sequencing] Primers hybridize to the P1 adapter sequence within the library template.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/abi-solid-sequencing] A set of four fluorescently labelled di-base probes compete for ligation to the sequencing primer.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/abi-solid-sequencing] Specificity of the di-base probe is achieved by interrogating every 1st and 2nd base in each ligation reaction.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/abi-solid-sequencing] Multiple cycles of ligation, detection and cleavage are performed with the number of cycles determining the eventual read length.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/abi-solid-sequencing] Following a series of ligation cycles, the extension product is removed and the template is reset with a primer complementary to the n-1 position for a second round of ligation cycles.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/abi-solid-sequencing] Five rounds of primer reset are completed for each sequence tag.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/abi-solid-sequencing] Through the primer reset process, each base is interrogated in two independent ligation reactions by two different primers.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/abi-solid-sequencing] For example, the base at read position 5 is assayed by primer number 2 in ligation cycle 2 and by primer number 3 in ligation cycle 1.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/abi-solid-sequencing] According to ABI, the SOLiD 3plus platform yields 60 gigabases of usable DNA data per run.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/abi-solid-sequencing] Due to the two base encoding system, an inherent accuracy check is built into the technology and offers 99.94% accuracy.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/abi-solid-sequencing] The chemistry of the systems also means that it is not hindered by homopolymers unlike the Roche 454 FLX system and so large and difficult homopolymer repeat regions are no longer a problem to sequence.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/abi-solid-sequencing] Naturally the technology will be used to sequence DNA, but because of the high parallel nature of all next generation technologies they also have applications in transcriptomics and epigenomics.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/abi-solid-sequencing] Microarrays was once the mainstay of the transcriptomics the last ten years and array based technology has subsequently branched out to other areas.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/abi-solid-sequencing] However, they are limited in that only information can be obtained for probes that are on the chip.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/abi-solid-sequencing] Only information for organisms for which chips are available can obtained, and they come with all the problems of hybridizing large numbers of molecules (differing hybridizing temperatures).
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/abi-solid-sequencing] RNA-Seq transcriptomics by next gen sequencing will mean these barriers no longer hold true.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/abi-solid-sequencing] Any organism's entire transcriptome could be potentially sequenced in one run (for very small bacterial genomes) and not only would the identification of each transcript be available but expression profiling is possible as quantitative reads can also be achieved.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/abi-solid-sequencing] Chromatin immunoprecipitation (ChIP) is a method for determining transcription factor binding sites and DNA-protein interactions.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/abi-solid-sequencing] It has in the past been combined with array technology (ChIP-chip) with some success.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/abi-solid-sequencing] Next gen sequencing can also be applied in this area.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/abi-solid-sequencing] Methylation immunoprecipitation (MeDIP) can also be performed and also on arrays.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/abi-solid-sequencing] The ability to learn more about methylation and TF binding sites on a genome wide scale is a valuable resource and could teach us much about disease and molecular biology in general.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] Risk factors include getting older, being male, smoking, previous chemotherapy or radiation therapy, myelodysplastic syndrome, and exposure to the chemical benzene.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] The underlying mechanism involves replacement of normal bone marrow with leukemia cells, which results in a drop in red blood cells, platelets, and normal white blood cells.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] Diagnosis is generally based on bone marrow aspiration and specific blood tests.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] AML has several subtypes for which treatments and outcomes may vary.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] The first-line treatment of AML is usually chemotherapy, intending to induce remission.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] People may then go on to receive additional chemotherapy, radiation therapy, or a stem cell transplant.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] The specific genetic mutations present within the cancer cells may guide therapy, as well as determine how long that person is likely to survive.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] Between 2017 and 2025, 12 new agents have been approved for AML in the U.S., including venetoclax (BCL2 inhibitor), gemtuzumab ozogamicin (CD33 antibody-drug conjugate), and several inhibitors targeting FMS-like tyrosine kinase 3, isocitrate dehydrogenase, and other pathways.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] Additionally, therapies like CPX351 and oral formulations of azacitidine and decitabine-cedazuridine have been introduced.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] Ongoing research is exploring menin inhibitors and other antibody-drug conjugates.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] Low-intensity treatment with azacitidine plus venetoclax has emerged as the most effective option for older or unfit AML patients, based on a network meta-analysis of 26 trials involving 4,920 participants.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] It showed the highest survival and remission rates, with low-dose cytarabine (LDAC) plus glasdegib and LDAC plus venetoclax also showing clinical benefit.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] In 2015, AML affected about one million people and resulted in 147,000 deaths globally.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] It most commonly occurs in older adults.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] Males are affected more often than females.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] As of 2015, the five-year survival rate was about 35% in people under 60 years old and 10% in people over 60 years old.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] Older people whose health is too poor for intensive chemotherapy have a typical survival of five to ten months.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] It accounts for roughly 1.1% of all cancer cases, and 1.8% of cancer deaths in the United States.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] Most signs and symptoms of AML are caused by the crowding out in bone marrow of space for normal blood cells to develop.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] A lack of normal white blood cell production makes people more susceptible to infections.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] A low red blood cell count (anemia) can cause fatigue, paleness, shortness of breath and palpitations.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] A lack of platelets can lead to easy bruising, bleeding from the nose (epistaxis), small blood vessels on the skin (petechiae) or gums, or bleeding with minor trauma.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] Other symptoms may include fever, fatigue worse than what can be attributed to anemia alone, weight loss, and loss of appetite.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] Enlargement of the spleen may occur in AML, but it is typically mild and asymptomatic.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] Lymph node swelling is rare in most types of AML, except for acute myelomonocytic leukemia (AMML).
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] The skin can be involved in the form of leukemia cutis; Sweet's syndrome; or non-specific findings: flat lesions (macules), raised lesion papules, pyoderma gangrenosum and vasculitis.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] Some people with AML may experience swelling of the gums because of infiltration of leukemic cells into the gum tissue.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] Involvement of other parts of the body, such as the gastrointestinal tract, respiratory tract, and other parts, is possible but less common.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] One area which has particular importance for treatment is whether there is involvement of the meninges around the central nervous system.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] Most cases of AML do not have exposure to any identified risk factors.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] However, several risk factors for developing AML have been identified.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] These include other blood disorders, chemical exposures, ionizing radiation, and genetic risk factors.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] Where a defined exposure to past chemotherapy, radiotherapy, toxin or hematologic malignancy is known, this is termed *secondary AML*.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] Other blood disorders, particularly myelodysplastic syndrome (MDS) and less commonly myeloproliferative neoplasms (MPN), can evolve into AML; the exact risk depends on the type of MDS/MPN.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] The presence of asymptomatic clonal hematopoiesis also raises the risk of transformation into AML.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] Exposure to chemotherapy, in particular alkylating antineoplastic agents, can increase the risk of subsequently developing AML.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] Other chemotherapy agents, including fludarabine, and topoisomerase II inhibitors are also associated with the development of AML; most commonly after 4–6 years and 1–3 years respectively.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] These are often associated with specific chromosomal abnormalities in the leukemic cells.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] Other chemical exposures associated with the development of AML include benzene, chloramphenicol, and phenylbutazone.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] The use of Agent Orange, a militarized herbicide used in the Vietnam War has been associated with the risk of AML due to the herbicide regularly having been contaminated by 2,3,7,8-tetrachlorodibenzo-p-dioxin (TCDD), the most toxic dioxin known.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] High amounts of ionizing radiation exposure, such as that used for radiotherapy used to treat some forms of cancer, can increase the risk of AML.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] People treated with ionizing radiation after treatment for prostate cancer, non-Hodgkin lymphoma, lung cancer, and breast cancer have the highest chance of acquiring AML, but this increased risk returns to the background risk observed in the general population after 12 years.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] Historically, survivors of the atomic bombings of Hiroshima and Nagasaki had an increased rate of AML, as did radiologists exposed to high levels of X-rays prior to the adoption of modern radiation safety practices.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] Traditionally, AML was considered sporadic, with only a few exceptions associated with rare hereditary conditions such as Down syndrome, Fanconi anemia, and telomere biology disorders.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] With the introduction of Next Generation Sequencing (NGS) in clinical work-up, it is now estimated that up to 5–15% of all AML cases carry a pathogenic variant in a cancer susceptibility gene.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] *Myeloid neoplasm with germline predisposition* is recognized as a distinct category in the WHO 2022 classification of haematolymphoid tumors.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] Being overweight and obese increase the risk of developing AML, as does any amount of active smoking.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] For reasons that may relate to substance or radiation exposure, certain occupations have a higher rate of AML; particularly work in the nuclear power industry, electronics or computer manufacturing, fishing, and animal slaughtering and processing.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] The malignant cell in AML is the myeloblast.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] In normal development of blood cells (hematopoiesis), the myeloblast is an immature precursor of myeloid white blood cells; a normal myeloblast will mature into a white blood cell such as an eosinophil, basophil, neutrophil, or monocyte.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] In AML, though, a single myeloblast accumulates genetic changes that stop maturation, increase its proliferation, and protect it from programmed cell death (apoptosis).
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] Much of the diversity and heterogeneity of AML is because leukemic transformation can occur at several different steps along the differentiation pathway.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] Genetic abnormalities or the stage at which differentiation was halted form part of modern classification systems.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] Specific cytogenetic abnormalities can be found in many people with AML; the types of chromosomal abnormalities often have prognostic significance.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] The chromosomal translocations encode abnormal fusion proteins, usually transcription factors whose altered properties may cause the "differentiation arrest".
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] For example, in APL, the t(15;17) translocation produces a PML-RARA fusion protein which binds to the retinoic acid receptor element in the promoters of several myeloid-specific genes and inhibits myeloid differentiation.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] The clinical signs and symptoms of AML result from the growth of leukemic clone cells, which tend to interfere with the development of normal blood cells in the bone marrow.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] This leads to neutropenia, anemia, and thrombocytopenia.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] Other symptoms can arise from the infiltration of malignant cells into parts of the body, such as the gingiva and skin.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] Many cells develop mutations in genes that affect epigenetics, such as DNA methylation.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] When these mutations occur, it is likely in the early stages of AML.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] Such mutations include in the DNA demethylase *TET2* and the metabolic enzymes *IDH1* and *IDH2*, which lead to the generation of a novel oncometabolite, *D*-2-hydroxyglutarate, which inhibits the activity of epigenetic enzymes such as *TET2*.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] Epigenetic mutations may lead to the silencing of tumor suppressor genes and/or the activation of proto-oncogenes.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] A complete blood count, which is a blood test, is one of the initial steps in the diagnosis of AML.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] It may reveal an excess of white blood cells (leukocytosis) or a decrease (leukopenia), and a low red blood cell count (anemia) and a low platelet count (thrombocytopenia) can also be commonly seen.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] A blood film may show leukemic blast cells.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] Inclusions within the cells called Auer rods, when seen, make the diagnosis highly likely.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] A definitive diagnosis requires a bone marrow aspiration and biopsy.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] A sample of marrow or blood is typically also tested for chromosomal abnormalities by routine cytogenetics or fluorescent *in situ* hybridization.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] Genetic studies may also be performed to look for specific mutations in genes such as *FLT3*, nucleophosmin, and *KIT*, which may influence disease outcome.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] Cytochemical stains on blood and bone marrow smears are helpful in the distinction of AML from ALL, and in the subclassification of AML.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] The combination of a myeloperoxidase or Sudan black stain and a nonspecific esterase stain will provide the desired information in most cases.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] The myeloperoxidase or Sudan black reactions are most useful in establishing the identity of AML and distinguishing it from ALL.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] The nonspecific esterase stain is used to identify a monocytic component in AMLs and to distinguish a poorly differentiated monoblastic leukemia from ALL.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] The standard classification scheme for AML is the World Health Organization (WHO) system.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] Myeloid sarcoma is also considered a subtype of AML independently of the blast count.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] The older French–American–British (FAB) classification, which is no longer widely used, is a bit more stringent, requiring a blast percentage of at least 30% in bone marrow or peripheral blood for the diagnosis of AML.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] Because acute promyelocytic leukemia has the highest curability and requires a unique form of treatment, it is important to quickly establish or exclude the diagnosis of this subtype of leukemia.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] Fluorescent *in situ* hybridization performed on blood or bone marrow is often used for this purpose, as it readily identifies the chromosomal translocation [t(15;17)(q22;q12);] that characterizes APL.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] There is also a need to molecularly detect the presence of PML/RARA fusion protein, which is an oncogenic product of that translocation.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] The WHO classification of AML attempts to be more clinically useful and to produce more meaningful prognostic information than the FAB criteria.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] The French–American–British (FAB) classification system is based on morphology to define specific immunotypes.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] The World Health Organization (WHO) classification reviews chromosome translocations and evidence of dysplasia.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] See French–American–British (FAB) classification system.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] Each of the WHO categories contains numerous descriptive subcategories of interest to the hematopathologist and oncologist; however, most clinically significant information in the WHO schema is communicated via categorization into one of the subtypes listed below.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] The revised fourth edition of the *WHO Classification of Tumours of Haematopoietic and Lymphoid Tissues* was released in 2016.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] This classification, based on a combination of genetic and immunophenotypic markers and morphology, defines the subtypes of AML and related neoplasms as shown below.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] In 2022, a new classification was published.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] Acute leukemias of ambiguous lineage (also known as mixed phenotype or biphenotypic acute leukemia) occur when the leukemic cells can not be classified as either myeloid or lymphoid cells, or where both types of cells are present.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] The French–American–British (FAB) classification system provides terminology that is still sometimes used.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] It remains a valuable diagnostic tool in areas without access to genetic testing.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] This system has largely been rendered obsolete by the WHO classification, which correlates more strongly with treatment outcomes.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] The FAB system divides AML into eight subtypes, M0 through M7, based on the cell type from which the leukemia developed and its degree of maturity.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] AML of types M0 to M2 may be called **acute myeloblastic leukemia**.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] Classification is done by examining the appearance of the malignant cells with light microscopy and/or by using cytogenetics to characterize any underlying chromosomal abnormalities.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] The subtypes have varying prognoses and responses to therapy.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] Six FAB subtypes (M1 through to M6) were initially proposed in 1976, although later revisions added M7 in 1985 and M0 in 1987.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] The morphologic subtypes of AML also include rare types not included in the FAB system, such as acute basophilic leukemia, which was proposed as a ninth subtype, M8, in 1999.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] The first-line treatment of acute myeloid leukemia consists primarily of chemotherapy, and is divided into two phases: induction and consolidation.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] The goal of induction therapy is to reduce the leukemic cells to undetectable levels (and thus achieve remission); the goal of consolidation therapy is to eliminate any residual undetectable disease and achieve a cure.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] Hematopoietic stem cell transplantation is usually considered if induction chemotherapy fails or after a person relapses.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] Transplantation is also sometimes used as front-line therapy for people with high-risk disease.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] Efforts to use targeted therapies such as tyrosine kinase inhibitors in AML continue.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] Various induction strategies are used, most of which center on daunorubicin (or a closely related drug) and cytarabine.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] Ziftomenib (Komzifti) was approved for medical use in the United States in November 2025.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] The goal and purpose of the induction phase is to reach a complete remission.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] Complete remission does not mean the disease has been cured; rather, it signifies that no disease can be detected with available diagnostic methods.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] All subtypes except acute promyelocytic leukemia are usually given induction chemotherapy with cytarabine and an anthracycline such as daunorubicin or idarubicin.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] This induction chemotherapy regimen is known as "7+3" (or "3+7"), because the cytarabine is given as a continuous IV infusion for seven consecutive days while the anthracycline is given for three consecutive days as an IV push.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] Response to this treatment varies with age, with people aged less than 60 years having better remission rates between 60% and 80%, while older people having lower remission rates between 33% and 60%.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] Because of the toxic effects of therapy and a greater chance of AML resistance to this induction therapy, different treatment, such as that in clinical trials might be offered to people 60–65 years or older.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] Acute promyelocytic leukemia is treated with all-*trans*-retinoic acid (ATRA) and either arsenic trioxide (ATO) monotherapy or an anthracycline.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] A syndrome similar to disseminated intravascular coagulation can develop during the initial few days of treatment or at the time the leukemia is diagnosed.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] Treatment can be complicated by a *differentiation syndrome* characterized by fever, fluid overload, and low oxygen levels.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] Acute promyelocytic leukemia is considered curable.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] There is insufficient evidence to determine if prescribing ATRA in addition to chemotherapy to adults who have other subtypes of acute myeloid leukemia is helpful.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] Even after complete remission is achieved, leukemic cells likely remain in numbers too small to be detected with current diagnostic techniques.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] If no consolidation therapy or further postremission therapy is given, almost all people with AML will eventually relapse.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] The specific type of postremission therapy is individualized based on a person's prognostic factors (see above) and general health.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] For good-prognosis leukemias (i.e., inv(16), t(8;21), and t(15;17)), people will typically undergo an additional three to five courses of intensive chemotherapy, known as consolidation chemotherapy.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] This generally involves cytarabine, with the doses administered being higher in younger patients, who are less likely to develop toxicity related to this treatment.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] Since 2017, a number of targeted therapies, such as Tyrosine Kinase Inhibitors and BCL-2 Inhibitors have been approved.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] These agents have expanded treatment options for patients with relapsed or refractory disease, as well as those who are unsuitable for intensive chemotherapy.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] Several studies demonstrate improved response rates and improved overall survival compared with previous standards of care.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] As well as their role in treating relapsed or refractory disease, inhibitors have been used as maintenance therapy after a patient has undergone Stem Cell Transplantation.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] Stem cell transplantation from a donor, called allogenic stem cell transplantation, is usually pursued if the prognosis is not considered favorable, a person can tolerate a transplant, and has a suitable donor.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] The basis of allogenic stem cell transplantation is on a *graft versus leukemia* effect whereby graft cells stimulate an immune response against leukemia cells.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] Unfortunately, this is accompanied by immune responses against other host organs, called a graft versus host disease.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] Theoretical therapies have been proposed based on the idea of using stem cell transplantation to replace blood stem cells with genetically modified versions with altered molecular markers, including CD45, which is present on most blood cells.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] A treatment would then be applied, such as an antibody-drug conjugate targeting the healthy version of the marker, in order to kill all blood cells with unmodified markers, including the original cells and the cancerous ones.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] Theoretical therapies have also been proposed to use genetic engineering to attach synthetic chimeric antigen receptors to T-cells.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] These would bind to markers present in high levels in AML cells, which include CD123 and CD135.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] T-cells could also be modified to target normal CD45 markers, but this requires also modifying the CD-45 of T-cells as well so that they do not target themselves.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] T-cell immunotherapies are being tested in mice and in early-phase clinical trials, but none has been approved as a standard of care for AML.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] Support is necessary throughout treatment because of problems associated with AML and also arising from treatment.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] Blood transfusions, including red blood cells and platelets, are necessary to maintain health levels, preventing complications of anemia (from low red blood cells) and bleeding (from low platelets).
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] AML leads to an increased risk of infections, particularly drug-resistant strains of bacteria and fungi.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] Antibiotics and antifungals can be used both to treat and to prevent these infections, particularly quinolones.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] Adding aerobic exercise to the standard of care may result in little to no difference in mortality, quality of life, and physical functioning.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] These exercises may result in a slight reduction in depression.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] Furthermore, aerobic physical exercises probably reduce fatigue.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] Recent research into the role of epigenetic regulators in hematopoietic malignancies has yielded new insights into the development of targeted epigenetic therapies as a supportive treatment for AML.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] The FDA has approved certain epigenetic-modifying drugs like ivosidenib and enasidenib, which are used in patients who can no longer receive intensive induction chemotherapy; specifically, they are involved in the therapy of IDH1 and IDH2 mutations.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] Further research must be done to prove the efficacy of epigenetic treatments, but the development of new epigenetic therapies along with immunotherapies holds potential in the future treatment of AML.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] Acute myeloid leukemia is rare in pregnancy, affecting about 1 in 75,000 to 100,000 pregnant women.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] It is diagnosed and treated similarly to AML in non-pregnancy, with a recommendation that it is treated urgently.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] However, treatment has significant implications for the pregnancy.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] First-trimester pregnancy is considered unlikely to be viable; pregnancy during weeks 24 – 36 requires consideration of the benefits of chemotherapy to the mother against the risks to the fetus; and there is a recommendation to consider delaying chemotherapy in very late pregnancy (> 36 weeks).
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] The "BE-CAR7" treatment was only trialled on two adults and eight children, with two-thirds of patients becoming cancer free.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] A further bone marrow transplant could help prevent the cancer returning.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] Multiple factors influence prognosis in AML, including the presence of specific mutations and a person's age with AML.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] In the United States between 2011 and 2016, the median survival of a person with AML was 8.5 months, with the 5-year survival being 24%.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] This declines with age, with the poorer prognosis being associated with an age greater than 65 years, and the poorest prognosis seen in those aged 75–84.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] As of 2001, cure rates in clinical trials have ranged from 20 to 45%; although clinical trials often include only younger people and those able to tolerate aggressive therapies.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] The overall cure rate for all people with AML (including the elderly and those unable to tolerate aggressive therapy) is likely lower.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] Cure rates for APL can be very high in some clinical trials.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] As of 2021, "[I]n APL, therapy with all-trans retinoic acid and arsenic trioxide results in estimated 10-year survival rates of ≥80% ...
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] Ongoing research in acute myeloid leukemia (AML) is progressing rapidly".
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] Arsenic trioxide and ATRA are the "most effective anti-APL agents" as shown by studies from China, India, and Iran.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] Secondary AML has a worse prognosis, as does treatment-related AML arising after chemotherapy for another previous malignancy.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] Both of these entities are associated with a high rate of unfavorable genetic mutations.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] Different genetic mutations are associated with different outcomes.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] Certain cytogenetic abnormalities are associated with very good outcomes (for example, the (15;17) translocation in APL).
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] About half of people with AML have "normal" cytogenetics lacking identifiable translocations or other large-scale anomalies; they fall into an intermediate risk group.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] Several other cytogenetic abnormalities are known to be associated with a poor prognosis and a high risk of relapse after treatment.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] A large number of molecular alterations are under study for their prognostic impact in AML.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] However, only *FLT3-ITD*, *NPM1*, *CEBPA*, and *c-KIT* are currently included in validated international risk stratification schemas.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] These are expected to increase rapidly in the near future.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] *FLT3* internal tandem duplications (ITDs) have been shown to confer a poorer prognosis in AML with normal cytogenetics.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] Several FLT3 inhibitors have undergone clinical trials, with mixed results.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] Two other mutations – *NPM1* and biallelic *CEBPA* are associated with improved outcomes, especially in people with normal cytogenetics, and are used in current risk stratification algorithms.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] Researchers are investigating the clinical significance of *c-KIT* mutations in AML.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] These are prevalent, and potentially clinically relevant because of the availability of tyrosine kinase inhibitors, such as imatinib and sunitinib that can block the activity of *c-KIT* pharmacologically.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] It is expected that additional markers (e.g., *RUNX1*, *ASXL1*, and *TP53*) that have consistently been associated with an inferior outcome will soon be included in these recommendations.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] The prognostic importance of other mutated genes (e.g., *DNMT3A*, *IDH1*, *IDH2*) is less clear.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] Elevated lactate dehydrogenase levels were also associated with poorer outcomes.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] Use of tobacco is associated with a person having a poorer prognosis, and people who are married and live together have a better prognosis.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] People who are treated at a place with a higher volume of AML have a better prognosis than those who are treated at those in the lowest quartile.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] As with most forms of cancer, performance status (i.e. the general physical condition and activity level of the person) plays a major role in prognosis as well.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] For people in remission after induction chemotherapy, residual leukemic cells (minimal residual disease) are associated with higher relapse rates and decreased survival.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] Furthermore, the presence of specific leukemic cells that are capable of initiating a relapse, the leukemia stem cell (a type of cancer stem cell) is associated with impaired survival and higher incidence of relapse.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] There were 19,950 new cases in the United States in 2016.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] In 2018, AML accounted for 1.2% of all cancer deaths in the United States.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] The incidence of AML increases with age and varies between countries.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] The median age when AML is diagnosed ranges between 63 and 71 years in the UK, Canada, Australia, and Sweden, compared with 40 to 45 years in India, Brazil, and Algeria.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] According to 2002 statistics, AML accounts for about 90% of all acute leukemias in adults and is rare in children.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] Acute leukemias consist of serious medical conditions relating to an original diagnosis of leukemia, where the abnormal blood cells are immature blood cells (blasts).
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] They are mostly classified in terms of myeloid cells or lymphoid cells.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] Based on these estimates, AML is about 78% of the total cases.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] The rate of therapy-related AML (AML caused by previous chemotherapy) is expected to rise with an increase in the use of chemotherapy, an aging population and more patients surviving their initial chemotherapy treatment; therapy-related disease accounts for just under 10% of all cases of AML.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] AML is slightly more common in men, with a male-to-female ratio of 1.3:1 to 1.4:1.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] Incidence is also seen to differ by ethnicity, with caucasians having higher recorded incidences and the lowest recorded incidences being in Pacific Islanders and native Alaskans.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] In the UK, AML accounts for 31% of all leukemia cases, and around 3,100 people were diagnosed with the disease each year in 2016–2018.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] Velpeau noted the blood of this person had a consistency "like gruel", and speculated the appearance of the blood was due to white corpuscles.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] In 1845, a series of people who died with enlarged spleens and changes in the "colors and consistencies of their blood" was reported by the Edinburgh-based pathologist J.H.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] Bennett; he used the term "leucocythemia" to describe this pathological condition.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] The term "leukemia" was coined by Rudolf Virchow, the renowned German pathologist, in 1856.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] As a pioneer in the use of the light microscope in pathology, Virchow was the first to describe the abnormal excess of white blood cells in people with the clinical syndrome described by Velpeau and Bennett.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] As Virchow was uncertain of the etiology of the white blood cell excess, he used the purely descriptive term "leukemia" (Greek: "white blood") to refer to the condition.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] Further advances in understanding AML occurred rapidly with the development of new technology.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] In 1877, Paul Ehrlich developed a technique of staining blood films, which allowed him to describe in detail normal and abnormal white blood cells.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] Wilhelm Ebstein introduced the term "acute leukemia" in 1889 to differentiate rapidly progressive and fatal leukemias from the more indolent chronic leukemias.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] The term "myeloid" was coined by Franz Ernst Christian Neumann in 1869, as he was the first to recognize white blood cells were made in the bone marrow (Greek: μυєλός, **myelos**, lit.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] '(bone) marrow') as opposed to the spleen.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] The technique of bone marrow examination to diagnose leukemia was first described in 1879 by Mosler.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] Finally, in 1900, the myeloblast, which is the malignant cell in AML, was characterized by Otto Naegeli, who divided the leukemias into myeloid and lymphocytic.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] In 2008, AML became the first cancer genome to be fully sequenced.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] DNA extracted from leukemic cells was compared to that of unaffected skin.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/acute-myeloid-leukaemia] The leukemic cells contained acquired mutations in several genes that had not previously been associated with the disease.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] Biologically relevant alternative splicing occurs as a normal phenomenon in eukaryotes, where it increases the number of proteins that can be encoded by the genome.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] Alternative splicing was first observed in 1977.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] The adenovirus produces five primary transcripts early in its infectious cycle, prior to viral DNA replication, and an additional one later, after DNA replication begins.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] The early primary transcripts continue to be produced after DNA replication begins.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] The additional primary transcript produced late in infection is large and comes from 5/6 of the 32kb adenovirus genome.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] This is much larger than any of the individual adenovirus mRNAs present in infected cells.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] Researchers found that the primary RNA transcript produced by adenovirus type 2 in the late phase was spliced in many different ways, resulting in mRNAs encoding different viral proteins.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] In addition, the primary transcript contained multiple polyadenylation sites, giving different 3' ends for the processed mRNAs.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] In 1981, the first example of alternative splicing in a transcript from a normal, endogenous gene was characterized.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] The gene encoding the thyroid hormone calcitonin was found to be alternatively spliced in mammalian cells.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] The primary transcript from this gene contains 6 exons; the calcitonin mRNA contains exons 1–4, and terminates after a polyadenylation site in exon 4.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] Another mRNA is produced from this pre-mRNA by skipping exon 4, and includes exons 1–3, 5, and 6.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] It encodes a protein known as CGRP (calcitonin gene related peptide).
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] Examples of alternative splicing in immunoglobulin gene transcripts in mammals were also observed in the early 1980s.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] Since then, many other examples of biologically relevant alternative splicing have been found in eukaryotes.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] The "record-holder" for alternative splicing is a *D. melanogaster* gene called Dscam, which could potentially have 38,016 splice variants.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] In 2021, it was discovered that the genome of adenovirus type 2, the adenovirus in which alternative splicing was first identified, was able to produce a much greater variety of splice variants than previously thought.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] By using next generation sequencing technology, researchers were able to update the human adenovirus type 2 transcriptome and document the presence of 904 splice variants produced by the virus through a complex pattern of alternative splicing.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] Very few of these splice variants have been shown to be functional, a point that the authors raise in their paper.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] Five basic modes of alternative splicing are generally recognized.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] In addition to these primary modes of alternative splicing, there are two other main mechanisms by which different mRNAs may be generated from the same gene; multiple promoters and multiple polyadenylation sites.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] Use of multiple promoters is properly described as a transcriptional regulation mechanism rather than alternative splicing; by starting transcription at different points, transcripts with different 5'-most exons can be generated.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] At the other end, multiple polyadenylation sites provide different 3' end points for the transcript.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] Both of these mechanisms are found in combination with alternative splicing and provide additional variety in mRNAs derived from a gene.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] These modes describe basic splicing mechanisms, but may be inadequate to describe complex splicing events.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] For instance, the figure to the right shows three spliceforms from the mouse hyaluronidase 3 gene.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] Comparing the exonic structure shown in the first line (green) with the one in the second line (yellow) shows intron retention, whereas the comparison between the second and the third spliceform (yellow vs. blue) exhibits exon skipping.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] A model nomenclature to uniquely designate all possible splicing patterns has recently been proposed.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] When the pre-mRNA has been transcribed from the DNA, it includes several introns and exons.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] (In nematodes, the mean is 4–5 exons and introns; in the fruit fly *Drosophila* there can be more than 100 introns and exons in one transcribed pre-mRNA.) The exons to be retained in the mRNA are determined during the splicing process.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] The regulation and selection of splice sites are done by trans-acting splicing activator and splicing repressor proteins as well as cis-acting elements within the pre-mRNA itself such as exonic splicing enhancers and exonic splicing silencers.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] The typical eukaryotic nuclear intron has consensus sequences defining important regions.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] Each intron has the sequence GU at its 5' end.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] The nucleotide at the branchpoint is always an A; the consensus around this sequence varies somewhat.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] In humans the branch site consensus sequence is yUnAy.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] The branch site is followed by a series of pyrimidines – the polypyrimidine tract – then by AG at the 3' end.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] Splicing of mRNA is performed by an RNA and protein complex known as the spliceosome, containing snRNPs designated U1, U2, U4, U5, and U6 (U3 is not involved in mRNA splicing).
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] U1 binds to the 5' GU and U2, with the assistance of the U2AF protein factors, binds to the branchpoint A within the branch site.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] The complex at this stage is known as the spliceosome A complex.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] Formation of the A complex is usually the key step in determining the ends of the intron to be spliced out, and defining the ends of the exon to be retained.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] (The U nomenclature derives from their high uridine content).
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] The U4,U5,U6 complex binds, and U6 replaces the U1 position.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] The remaining complex then performs two transesterification reactions.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] In the first transesterification, 5' end of the intron is cleaved from the upstream exon and joined to the branch site A by a 2',5'-phosphodiester linkage.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] In the second transesterification, the 3' end of the intron is cleaved from the downstream exon, and the two exons are joined by a phosphodiester bond.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] The intron is then released in lariat form and degraded.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] Splicing is regulated by trans-acting proteins (repressors and activators) and corresponding cis-acting regulatory sites (silencers and enhancers) on the pre-mRNA.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] However, as part of the complexity of alternative splicing, it is noted that the effects of a splicing factor are frequently position-dependent.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] That is, a splicing factor that serves as a splicing activator when bound to an intronic enhancer element may serve as a repressor when bound to its splicing element in the context of an exon, and vice versa.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] The secondary structure of the pre-mRNA transcript also plays a role in regulating splicing, such as by bringing together splicing elements or by masking a sequence that would otherwise serve as a binding element for a splicing factor.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] Together, these elements form a "splicing code" that governs how splicing will occur under different cellular conditions.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] There are two major types of cis-acting RNA sequence elements present in pre-mRNAs and they have corresponding trans-acting RNA-binding proteins.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] Splicing *silencers* are sites to which splicing repressor proteins bind, reducing the probability that a nearby site will be used as a splice junction.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] These can be located in the intron itself (intronic splicing silencers, ISS) or in a neighboring exon (exonic splicing silencers, ESS).
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] They vary in sequence, as well as in the types of proteins that bind to them.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] The majority of splicing repressors are heterogeneous nuclear ribonucleoproteins (hnRNPs) such as hnRNPA1 and polypyrimidine tract-binding protein (PTB).
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] Splicing *enhancers* are sites to which splicing activator proteins bind, increasing the probability that a nearby site will be used as a splice junction.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] These also may occur in the intron (intronic splicing enhancers, ISE) or exon (exonic splicing enhancers, ESE).
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] Most of the activator proteins that bind to ISEs and ESEs are members of the SR protein family.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] Such proteins contain RNA recognition motifs and arginine and serine-rich (RS) domains.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] In general, the determinants of splicing work in an inter-dependent manner that depends on context, so that the rules governing how splicing is regulated form a splicing code.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] The presence of a particular cis-acting RNA sequence element may increase the probability that a nearby site will be spliced in some cases, but decrease the probability in other cases, depending on context.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] The context within which regulatory elements act includes cis-acting context that is established by the presence of other RNA sequence features, and trans-acting context that is established by cellular conditions.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] For example, some cis-acting RNA sequence elements influence splicing only if multiple elements are present in the same region so as to establish context.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] As another example, a cis-acting element can have opposite effects on splicing, depending on which proteins are expressed in the cell (e.g., neuronal versus non-neuronal PTB).
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] The adaptive significance of splicing silencers and enhancers is attested by studies showing that there is strong selection in human genes against mutations that produce new silencers or disrupt existing enhancers.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] Pre-mRNAs from the *Drosophila melanogaster* gene *dsx* contain 6 exons.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] In males, exons 1, 2, 3, 5, and 6 are joined to form the mRNA, which encodes a transcriptional regulatory protein required for male development.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] In females, exons 1, 2, 3, and 4 are joined, and a polyadenylation signal in exon 4 causes cleavage of the mRNA at that point.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] The resulting mRNA is a transcriptional regulatory protein required for female development.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] The intron upstream from exon 4 has a polypyrimidine tract that does not match the consensus sequence well, so that U2AF proteins bind poorly to it without assistance from splicing activators.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] This 3' splice acceptor site is therefore not used in males.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] Females, however, produce the splicing activator Transformer (Tra) (see below).
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] The SR protein Tra2 is produced in both sexes and binds to an ESE in exon 4; if Tra is present, it binds to Tra2 and, along with another SR protein, forms a complex that assists U2AF proteins in binding to the weak polypyrimidine tract.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] U2 is recruited to the associated branchpoint, and this leads to inclusion of exon 4 in the mRNA.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] Pre-mRNAs of the *Transformer* (Tra) gene of *Drosophila melanogaster* undergo alternative splicing via the alternative acceptor site mode.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] The gene Tra encodes a protein that is expressed only in females.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] The primary transcript of this gene contains an intron with two possible acceptor sites.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] In males, the upstream acceptor site is used.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] This causes a longer version of exon 2 to be included in the processed transcript, including an early stop codon.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] The resulting mRNA encodes a truncated protein product that is inactive.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] Females produce the master sex determination protein Sex lethal (Sxl).
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] The Sxl protein is a splicing repressor that binds to an ISS in the RNA of the Tra transcript near the upstream acceptor site, preventing U2AF protein from binding to the polypyrimidine tract.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] This prevents the use of this junction, shifting the spliceosome binding to the downstream acceptor site.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] Splicing at this point bypasses the stop codon, which is excised as part of the intron.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] The resulting mRNA encodes an active Tra protein, which itself is a regulator of alternative splicing of other sex-related genes (see *dsx* above).
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] Multiple isoforms of the Fas receptor protein are produced by alternative splicing.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] Two normally occurring isoforms in humans are produced by an exon-skipping mechanism.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] An mRNA including exon 6 encodes the membrane-bound form of the Fas receptor, which promotes apoptosis, or programmed cell death.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] Increased expression of Fas receptor in skin cells chronically exposed to the sun, and absence of expression in skin cancer cells, suggests that this mechanism may be important in elimination of pre-cancerous cells in humans.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] If exon 6 is skipped, the resulting mRNA encodes a soluble Fas protein that does not promote apoptosis.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] The inclusion or skipping of the exon depends on two antagonistic proteins, TIA-1 and polypyrimidine tract-binding protein (PTB).
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] This mechanism is an example of exon definition in splicing.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] A spliceosome assembles on an intron, and the snRNP subunits fold the RNA so that the 5' and 3' ends of the intron are joined.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] However, recently studied examples such as this one show that there are also interactions between the ends of the exon.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] In this particular case, these exon definition interactions are necessary to allow the binding of core splicing factors prior to assembly of the spliceosomes on the two flanking introns.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] HIV, the retrovirus that causes AIDS in humans, produces a single primary RNA transcript, which is alternatively spliced in multiple ways to produce over 40 different mRNAs.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] Equilibrium among differentially spliced transcripts provides multiple mRNAs encoding different products that are required for viral multiplication.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] One of the differentially spliced transcripts contains the *tat* gene, in which exon 2 is a cassette exon that may be skipped or included.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] The inclusion of tat exon 2 in the RNA is regulated by competition between the splicing repressor hnRNP A1 and the SR protein SC35.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] Within exon 2 an exonic splicing silencer sequence (ESS) and an exonic splicing enhancer sequence (ESE) overlap.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] If A1 repressor protein binds to the ESS, it initiates cooperative binding of multiple A1 molecules, extending into the 5' donor site upstream of exon 2 and preventing the binding of the core splicing factor U2AF35 to the polypyrimidine tract.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] If SC35 binds to the ESE, it prevents A1 binding and maintains the 5' donor site in an accessible state for assembly of the spliceosome.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] Competition between the activator and repressor ensures that both mRNA types (with and without exon 2) are produced.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] Genuine alternative splicing occurs in both protein-coding genes and non-coding genes to produce multiple products (proteins or non-coding RNAs).
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] External information is needed in order to decide which product is made, given a DNA sequence and the initial transcript.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] Since the methods of regulation are inherited, this provides novel ways for mutations to affect gene expression.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] Alternative splicing may provide evolutionary flexibility.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] A single point mutation may cause a given exon to be occasionally excluded or included from a transcript during splicing, allowing production of a new protein isoform without loss of the original protein.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] Studies have identified intrinsically disordered regions (see Intrinsically unstructured proteins) as enriched in the non-constitutive exons suggesting that protein isoforms may display functional diversity due to the alteration of functional modules within these regions.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] Such functional diversity achieved by isoforms is reflected by their expression patterns and can be predicted by machine learning approaches.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] Comparative studies indicate that alternative splicing preceded multicellularity in evolution, and suggest that this mechanism might have been co-opted to assist in the development of multicellular organisms.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] Research based on the Human Genome Project and other genome sequencing has shown that humans have only about 30% more genes than the roundworm *Caenorhabditis elegans*, and only about twice as many as the fly *Drosophila melanogaster*.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] This finding led to speculation that the perceived greater complexity of humans, or vertebrates generally, might be due to higher rates of alternative splicing in humans than are found in invertebrates.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] Another study, however, proposed that these results were an artifact of the different numbers of ESTs available for the various organisms.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] When they compared alternative splicing frequencies in random subsets of genes from each organism, the authors concluded that vertebrates do have higher rates of alternative splicing than invertebrates.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] Changes in the RNA processing machinery may lead to mis-splicing of multiple transcripts, while single-nucleotide alterations in splice sites or cis-acting splicing regulatory sites may lead to differences in splicing of a single gene, and thus in the mRNA produced from a mutant gene's transcripts.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] A study in 2005 involving probabilistic analyses indicated that greater than 60% of human disease-causing mutations affect splicing rather than directly affecting coding sequences.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] A more recent study indicates that one-third of all hereditary diseases are likely to have a splicing component.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] Regardless of exact percentage, a number of splicing-related diseases do exist.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] As described below, a prominent example of splicing-related diseases is cancer.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] Abnormally spliced mRNAs are also found in a high proportion of cancerous cells.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] Combined RNA-Seq and proteomics analyses have revealed striking differential expression of splice isoforms of key proteins in important cancer pathways.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] It is not always clear whether such aberrant patterns of splicing contribute to the cancerous growth, or are merely consequence of cellular abnormalities associated with cancer.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] For certain types of cancer, like in colorectal and prostate, the number of splicing errors per cancer has been shown to vary greatly between individual cancers, a phenomenon referred to as transcriptome instability.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] Transcriptome instability has further been shown to correlate greatly with reduced expression level of splicing factor genes.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] Mutation of *DNMT3A* has been demonstrated to contribute to hematologic malignancies, and that *DNMT3A*-mutated cell lines exhibit transcriptome instability as compared to their isogenic wildtype counterparts.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] In fact, there is actually a reduction of alternative splicing in cancerous cells compared to normal ones, and the types of splicing differ; for instance, cancerous cells show higher levels of intron retention than normal cells, but lower levels of exon skipping.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] Some of the differences in splicing in cancerous cells may be due to the high frequency of somatic mutations in splicing factor genes, and some may result from changes in phosphorylation of trans-acting splicing factors.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] Others may be produced by changes in the relative amounts of splicing factors produced; for instance, breast cancer cells have been shown to have increased levels of the splicing factor SF2/ASF.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] One study found that a relatively small percentage (383 out of over 26000) of alternative splicing variants were significantly higher in frequency in tumor cells than normal cells, suggesting that there is a limited set of genes which, when mis-spliced, contribute to tumor development.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] It is believed however that the deleterious effects of mis-spliced transcripts are usually safeguarded and eliminated by a cellular posttranscriptional quality control mechanism termed nonsense-mediated mRNA decay [NMD].
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] One example of a specific splicing variant associated with cancers is in one of the human DNMT genes.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] Three DNMT genes encode enzymes that add methyl groups to DNA, a modification that often has regulatory effects.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] Several abnormally spliced DNMT3B mRNAs are found in tumors and cancer cell lines.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] In two separate studies, expression of two of these abnormally spliced mRNAs in mammalian cells caused changes in the DNA methylation patterns in those cells.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] Cells with one of the abnormal mRNAs also grew twice as fast as control cells, indicating a direct contribution to tumor development by this product.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] Another example is the *Ron* (*MST1R*) proto-oncogene.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] An important property of cancerous cells is their ability to move and invade normal tissue.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] Production of an abnormally spliced transcript of *Ron* has been found to be associated with increased levels of the SF2/ASF in breast cancer cells.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] The abnormal isoform of the Ron protein encoded by this mRNA leads to cell motility.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] Overexpression of a truncated splice variant of the FOSB gene – ΔFosB – in a specific population of neurons in the nucleus accumbens has been identified as the causal mechanism involved in the induction and maintenance of an addiction to drugs and natural rewards.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] Recent provocative studies point to a key function of chromatin structure and histone modifications in alternative splicing regulation.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] These insights suggest that epigenetic regulation determines not only what parts of the genome are expressed but also how they are spliced.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] Transcriptome-wide analysis of alternative splicing is typically performed by high-throughput RNA-sequencing.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] Most commonly, by short-read sequencing, such as by Illumina instrumentation.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] But even more informative, by long-read sequencing, such as by Nanopore or PacBio instrumentation.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] Transcriptome-wide analyses can for example be used to measure the amount of deviating alternative splicing, such as in a cancer cohort.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] Deep sequencing technologies have been used to conduct genome-wide analyses of both unprocessed and processed mRNAs; thus providing insights into alternative splicing.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] For example, results from use of deep sequencing indicate that, in humans, an estimated 95% of transcripts from multiexon genes undergo alternative splicing, with a number of pre-mRNA transcripts spliced in a tissue-specific manner.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] Functional genomics and computational approaches based on multiple instance learning have also been developed to integrate RNA-seq data to predict functions for alternatively spliced isoforms.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] Deep sequencing has also aided in the *in vivo* detection of the transient lariats that are released during splicing, the determination of branch site sequences, and the large-scale mapping of branchpoints in human pre-mRNA transcripts.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] More historically, alternatively spliced transcripts have been found by comparing EST sequences, but this requires sequencing of very large numbers of ESTs.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] Most EST libraries come from a very limited number of tissues, so tissue-specific splice variants are likely to be missed in any case.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] High-throughput approaches to investigate splicing have, however, been developed, such as: DNA microarray–based analyses, RNA-binding assays, and deep sequencing.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] These methods can be used to screen for polymorphisms or mutations in or around splicing elements that affect protein binding.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] When combined with splicing assays, including *in vivo* reporter gene assays, the functional effects of polymorphisms or mutations on the splicing of pre-mRNA transcripts can then be analyzed.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] In microarray analysis, arrays of DNA fragments representing individual exons (*e.g.* Affymetrix exon microarray) or exon/exon boundaries (*e.g.* arrays from ExonHit or Jivan) have been used.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] The array is then probed with labeled cDNA from tissues of interest.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] The probe cDNAs bind to DNA from the exons that are included in mRNAs in their tissue of origin, or to DNA from the boundary where two exons have been joined.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] This can reveal the presence of particular alternatively spliced mRNAs.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] CLIP (Cross-linking and immunoprecipitation) uses UV radiation to link proteins to RNA molecules in a tissue during splicing.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] A trans-acting splicing regulatory protein of interest is then precipitated using specific antibodies.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] When the RNA attached to that protein is isolated and cloned, it reveals the target sequences for that protein.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] Use of the MEGAshift method has provided insights into the regulation of alternative splicing by allowing for the identification of sequences in pre-mRNA transcripts surrounding alternatively spliced exons that mediate binding to different splicing factors, such as ASF/SF2 and PTB.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] This approach has also been used to aid in determining the relationship between RNA secondary structure and the binding of splicing factors.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] Use of reporter assays makes it possible to find the splicing proteins involved in a specific alternative splicing event by constructing reporter genes that will express one of two different fluorescent proteins depending on the splicing reaction that occurs.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] This method has been used to isolate mutants affecting splicing and thus to identify novel splicing regulatory proteins inactivated in those mutants.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] Recent advancements in protein structure prediction have facilitated the development of new tools for genome annotation and alternative splicing analysis.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] For instance, isoform.io, a platform guided by protein structure predictions, has evaluated hundreds of thousands of isoforms of human protein-coding genes assembled from numerous RNA sequencing experiments across a variety of human tissues.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] This comprehensive analysis has led to the identification of numerous isoforms with more confidently predicted structure and potentially superior function compared to canonical isoforms in the latest human gene database.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] By integrating structural predictions with expression and evolutionary evidence, this approach has demonstrated the potential of protein structure prediction as a tool for refining the annotation of the human genome.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] There is a collection of alternative splicing databases.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/alternative-splicing] These databases are useful for finding genes having pre-mRNAs undergoing alternative splicing and alternative splicing events or to study the functional impact of alternative splicing.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-atlas] TCGA was supervised by the National Cancer Institute's Center for Cancer Genomics and the National Human Genome Research Institute funded by the US government.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-atlas] A three-year pilot project, begun in 2006, focused on characterization of three types of human cancers: glioblastoma multiforme, lung squamous carcinoma, and ovarian serous adenocarcinoma.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-atlas] In 2009, it expanded into phase II, which planned to complete the genomic characterization and sequence analysis of 20–25 different tumor types by 2014.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-atlas] Ultimately, TCGA surpassed that goal, characterizing 33 cancer types including 10 rare cancers.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-atlas] The project initially set out to collect and characterize 500 patient samples, more than most genomics studies of its time, and used a variety of different molecular techniques.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-atlas] Techniques included gene expression profiling, copy number variation profiling, SNP genotyping, genome wide DNA methylation profiling, microRNA profiling, and exon sequencing.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-atlas] With restraints of nascent technology and costs at the start of the project, many array-based technologies and limited targeted gene sequencing were performed.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-atlas] During phase II, TCGA was able to begin performing whole exome sequencing and whole transcriptome sequencing on all cases, and whole genome sequencing on 10% of the cases used in the project.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-atlas] The goal of TCGA's pilot project was to establish an infrastructure to collect, molecularly characterize, and analyze 500 cancers and matched controls.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-atlas] The work required extensive cooperation among a team of scientists from various institutions and assessment of multiple burgeoning high-throughput technologies.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-atlas] TCGA wanted to not only generate high-quality and biologically meaningful genomic data, but also make that data freely available to the cancer research community.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-atlas] Three tumor types were explored during the pilot phase, glioblastoma multiforme (GBM) and high-grade serous ovarian adenocarcinoma, and lung squamous carcinoma.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-atlas] Following success of the pilot phase, TCGA expanded its effort to characterize additional cancer types and provide a rich and large genomic data set for further cancer research discovery.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-atlas] TCGA was co-managed by scientists and managers from the National Cancer Institute (NCI) and the National Human Genome Research Institute (NHGRI).
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-atlas] With the expansion of TCGA from the pilot phase to Phase II in October 2009, NCI created a TCGA Program Office to help manage the project.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-atlas] Jean Claude Zenklusen has been the director of the office since August 2013.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-atlas] The TCGA Program Office was responsible for the operation of six Genome Characterization Centers, seven Genome Analysis Centers, the Biospecimen Core Resource, the Data Coordination Center, and approximately one third of the sequencing done for the project by the three Genome Sequencing Centers.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-atlas] In addition, the TCGA Project Office was responsible for coordinating the accrual of tissues for TCGA.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-atlas] Carolyn Hutter, project manager for NHGRI, directed two thirds of the sequencing at the Genome Sequencing Centers.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-atlas] Members from the NCI and the NHGRI teams, along with principal investigators funded by the project, comprised the Steering Committee.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-atlas] Tissue requirements varied from tissue type to tissue type and from cancer type to cancer type.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-atlas] Disease experts from the project's Disease Working Groups helped to define the characteristics of the typical tissue samples accrued as "standard of care" in the United States and how TCGA could best utilize the tissue.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-atlas] For example, the Brain Disease Working Group determined that samples containing more than 50% necrosis would not be suitable for TCGA and that 80% tumor nuclei were required in the viable portion of the tumor.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-atlas] TCGA followed some general guidelines as a starting point for collecting samples from any type of tumor, including a minimum of 200 mg in size, no less than 80% tumor nuclei and a matched source of germline DNA (such as blood or purified DNA).
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-atlas] In addition, institutions submitting tissues to TCGA were required to include a minimal clinical data set as defined by the Disease Working Group, signed consents which have been approved by their institution's IRB, as well as a material transfer agreement with TCGA.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-atlas] RFQs were primarily used for the collection of retrospective samples from established banks while RFPs were used for the prospective collection of samples.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-atlas] TCGA finalized sample collection in December, 2013, with nearly 20,000 biospecimens.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-atlas] Institutions that contributed samples to TCGA were paid, and gained advance access to molecular data generated on their samples, while maintaining a link between the TCGA unique identifier and their own unique identifier.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-atlas] This permitted contributing institutions to link back to the clinical data for their samples and to enter into collaborations with other institutions that had similar data on TCGA samples, thus increasing the power of outcome analysis.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-atlas] TCGA managed a number of different types of centers that were funded to generate and analyze data.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-atlas] TCGA was the first large-scale genomics project funded by the NIH to include significant resources to bioinformatic discovery.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-atlas] The NCI has devoted 50% of TCGA appropriated funds, approximately $12M/year, to fund bioinformatic discovery.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-atlas] Genome Characterization Centers and Genome Sequencing Centers generated data.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-atlas] Two separate Genome Data Analysis Centers utilized the data for bioinformatic discovery.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-atlas] Two centers were funded to isolate biomolecules from patient samples and one center is funded to store the data.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-atlas] This workflow has evolved over the years and is now known as NCI's Genome Characterization Pipeline.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-atlas] The Biospecimen Core Resource (BCR) was responsible for verifying the quality and quantity of tissue shipped by tissue source sites, isolating DNA and RNA from the samples, performing quality control of these biomolecules, and shipping processed samples to the GSCs and GCCs.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-atlas] The International Genomics Consortium was awarded the contract to initiate the BCR for the pilot project.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-atlas] There were two BCRs funded by NCI at the start of the full project: Nationwide Children's Hospital and the International Genomics Consortium.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-atlas] The BCRs were recompeted in 2010 and Nationwide Children's Hospital was awarded the contract.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-atlas] Three Genome Sequencing Centers (GCCs) were co-funded by NCI and NHGRI: the Broad Institute, McDonnell Genome Institute at Washington University and Baylor College of Medicine.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-atlas] All three of these sequencing centers have shifted from Sanger sequencing to next-generation sequencing (NGS).
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-atlas] A variety of NGS technologies were tested and implemented simultaneously.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-atlas] The NCI funded seven Genome characterization centers: the Broad Institute, Harvard, University of North Carolina, MD Anderson Cancer Center, Van Andel Institute, Baylor College of Medicine and the British Columbia Cancer Center.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-atlas] The Data Coordinating Center (DCC) was the central repository for TCGA data.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-atlas] It was also responsible for the quality control of data entering the TCGA database.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-atlas] The DCC also maintained the TCGA Data Portal, which was where users could access processed TCGA data.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-atlas] This work was performed under contract by bioinformatics scientists and developers from SRA International, Inc.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-atlas] The DCC did not host raw sequencing data, however.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-atlas] NCI's Cancer Genomics Hub (CGHub) was the secure repository for storing, cataloging, and accessing sequence-related data.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-atlas] This work was performed by scientists and staff at the University of California, Santa Cruz Genomics Institute.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-atlas] Since 2017, all types of data were moved to NCI's Genomic Data Commons.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-atlas] Seven Genome Data Analysis Centers (GDACs) funded by the NCI/NHGRI were responsible for the integration of data across all characterization and sequencing centers as well as biological interpretation of TCGA data.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-atlas] The GDACs included The Broad Institute, University of North Carolina, Oregon Health and Science University, University of California, Santa Cruz, MD Anderson Cancer Center, Memorial Sloan Kettering Cancer Center, and The Institute for Systems Biology.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-atlas] All seven GDACs worked together to develop an integrated data analysis pipeline.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-atlas] A preliminary list of tumors for TCGA to study was generated by compiling incidence and survival statistics from the SEER Cancer Statistic website.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-atlas] In addition, U.S. current “Standard of Care” was considered when choosing the top 25 tumor types, as TCGA was targeting tumor types where resection prior to adjunct therapy was the standard of care.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-atlas] Availability of samples also played a critical role in determining which tumor types to study and the order in which tumor projects are started; the more common the cancer type, the more likely that samples would be accrued quickly for study.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-atlas] This resulted in common tumor types, such as colon, lung and breast cancer becoming the first tumor types entered into the project, before rare tumor types.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-atlas] TCGA began accruing samples for all of these tumor types simultaneously.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-atlas] The tumor types with the most samples accrued were entered into the characterization pipeline first.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-atlas] The rarer tumor types which were more difficult to accrue and tumor types for which TCGA could not identify a source of high-quality samples were entered into the TCGA production pipeline in the second year of the project.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-atlas] This gave the TCGA Program Office additional time to accrue sufficient samples for the project.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-atlas] TCGA and the Mouse Organogenesis Cell Atlas (MOCA) were elaborated by machine learning and deep learning to compare and find correlation between cancer and embryonic cells in early cell development and differentiation.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-atlas] They were also applied to distinguish changes in gene expression patterns between various types of tumors from an unknown source.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-atlas] In 2008, the TCGA published its first results on glioblastoma multiforme (GBM) in *Nature*.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-atlas] These first results characterized and analyzed 91 tumor-normal matched pairs.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-atlas] While 587 biospecimens were collected for the study, most were rejected during quality control: the tumor samples needed to contain at least 80% tumor nuclei and no more than 50% necrosis, and a secondary pathology assessment had to agree that the original diagnosis of GBM was accurate.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-atlas] A last batch of samples was excluded because the DNA or RNA collected was not of sufficient quality or quantity to be analyzed by all of the different platforms used in the study.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-atlas] All of the data from this study, as well as data that has been collected since the publication were made publicly available at TCGA's Data Coordinating Center (DCC) for public access (later moved toe the Genomic Data Commons).
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-atlas] Most of the processed TCGA data is completely open access.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-atlas] For data that could potentially identify specific patients, users apply for controlled-data access to the Data Access Committee (DAC), which evaluates whether the end user is a bona fide researcher and is asking a legitimate scientific question that merits access to individual-level data.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-atlas] Data access credentials are now managed through NIH's dbGAP.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-atlas] Since the publication of the first marker paper, several analysis groups within the TCGA Network have presented more detailed analyses of the glioblastoma data.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-atlas] An analysis group led by Roel Verhaak, PhD, Katherine A.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-atlas] Neil Hayes, MD, successfully correlated glioma gene expression subtypes with genomic abnormalities.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-atlas] The DNA methylation data analysis team, led by Houtan Noushmehr, PhD and Peter Laird, PhD, identified a distinct subset of glioma samples which displays concerted hypermethylation at a large number of loci, indicating the existence of a glioma-CpG island methylator phenotype (G-CIMP).
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-atlas] G-CIMP tumors belong to the proneural subgroup and were tightly associated with IDH1 somatic mutations.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-atlas] TCGA reported on mRNA expression, microRNA expression, promoter methylation, DNA copy number, and exome sequencing of 316 tumor samples of high grade serous ovarian cancer in *Nature* in June 2011.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-atlas] The researchers found mutations of the gene *TP53* in an overwhelming 96% of the cases analyzed, Recurrent mutations at lower frequency were found in a handful of other genes, including *NF1*, *BRCA1*, *BRCA2*, *RB1* and *CDK12*.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-atlas] TCGA researchers were also able to identify gene expression patterns that correlated with patient survival.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-atlas] They defined four subtypes of the cancer according to gene expression and DNA methylation patterns: immunoreactive, differentiated, proliferative, and mesenchymal.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-atlas] They also identified 68 genes as potential drug targets.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-atlas] TCGA reported on the exome sequence, DNA copy number, promoter methylation and messenger RNA characterization of 276 tumor samples of colon and rectal cancers in *Nature* in July 2012.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-atlas] 97 of the samples also underwent ultra-low coverage whole genome sequencing.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-atlas] TCGA researchers discovered the same type of alterations in colon and rectal tumors, indicating that they are a single type of cancer.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-atlas] Some differences, such as hypermethylation, were apparent in tumors originating in the right colon.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-atlas] A subset of the tumors were found to be hypermutated; a majority of those also had high microsatellite instability.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-atlas] Two dozen significantly mutated genes and recurring copy number alterations were found.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-atlas] The study suggested new markers for aggressive colorectal carcinoma and an important role for MYC-directed transcriptional activation and repression.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-atlas] Fueled by the American Recovery and Reinvestment Act of 2009, NIH extended TCGA to cover 20 types of cancer.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-atlas] This included an effort to study rare cancers, which was enabled with support from patients, patient advocacy groups, and doctors.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-atlas] Starting in 2011, TCGA began holding Annual Scientific Symposiums to discuss and share novel biological discoveries on cancer, analytical methods and translational approaches using the data.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-atlas] In December 2013, TCGA concluded sample collection, having shipped and processed over 20,000 specimens.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-atlas] By the project’s completion, TCGA published “marker papers” describing the characterization and basic analyses covering 33 cancer types.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-atlas] For several cancer types, such as bladder urothelial carcinoma and GBM, additional cases were collected and a second analysis was performed.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-atlas] In 2013, TCGA published an initial Pan-Cancer analysis describing the "mutational landscape" defined as frequently recurring mutations identified from exome sequencing of 3,281 tumours from 12 commonly occurring cancer subtypes.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-atlas] In 2018, the TCGA Research Network published what is collectively known as the Pan-Cancer Atlas: a collection of 35 papers summarizing the work accomplished by TCGA and describing overarching themes of cancer biology elucidated by analyzing all of TCGA data as a whole.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-atlas] The completion of the Pan-Cancer Atlas marked the official end of TCGA as a program, though the data, analysis methods, and other resources produced by TCGA continues to serve as a resource for researchers.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-atlas] For example, TCGA’s whole-genome data were analyzed as part of the Pan-Cancer Analysis of Whole Genomes (PCAWG), an international effort to analyze 2,600 cancer whole genomes to understand somatic and germline variations in both coding and non-coding regions.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-atlas] TCGA researchers also set out to systematically study the non-coding regions of the genome of multiple cancers.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-atlas] The team applied the assay for transposase-accessible chromatin using sequencing (ATAC-seq) to 410 TCGA tumor samples covering 23 primary cancers in order to gain insights into gene dysregulation in cancer.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-atlas] ATAC-seq is a low-cost method for identifying regions of open or active chromatin and positions of DNA-binding proteins.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-atlas] Through ATAC-seq, researchers were able to identify a tens of thousands of potential DNA regulatory elements specific to different cancers and cell types.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-atlas] This provided insights into how gene dysregulation could help drive cancer initiation and progression.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-atlas] Understanding chromatin accessibility of known immune cell-specific regulatory elements also provided clues into the immune microenvironment and the availability of immunotherapy targets.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-atlas] The study, “The chromatin landscape of primary human cancers,” was published in 2018 in *Science*.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-project] The **Cancer Genome Project** is part of the cancer, aging, and somatic mutation research based at the Wellcome Trust Sanger Institute in the United Kingdom.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-project] It aims to identify sequence variants/mutations critical in the development of human cancers.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-project] Like The Cancer Genome Atlas project within the United States, the Cancer Genome Project represents an effort in the war on cancer to improve cancer diagnosis, treatment, and prevention through a better understanding of the molecular basis of the disease.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-project] The Cancer Genome Project was launched by Michael Stratton in 2000, and Peter Campbell is now the group leader of the project.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-project] The project works to combine knowledge of the human genome sequence with high throughput mutation detection techniques.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-project] The project operates within the scope of the International Cancer Genome Consortium, working with the other participating organizations and countries to build a database of genomic changes present in different types of cancer.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-project] The somatic mutation information gathered by the project can be located in the COSMIC database.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-project] The Wellcome Trust Sanger Institute's project currently has several internal partners that each focus on different types of cancer and mutagenesis utilizing different methods.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-project] Research goes beyond just sequencing to include therapeutic biomarker discoveries made utilizing bioinformatics programs.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-project] Among these discoveries are drug sensitivity biomarkers and inhibitor biomarkers.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-project] These discoveries paired with the evolution of DNA sequencing technologies to next-generation sequencing techniques, are important in potential disease treatment and may even help lead to more personalized medicine for cancer patients.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-project] The goals of the project are to help sequence and catalog different cancer genomes.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-project] Beyond just sequencing the project's internal partners each have different areas of focus that will assist in the project's overall goal of determining unique ways for early detection of cancer, better prevention, and improved treatment for patients.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-project] The following groups are internal partners at the Wellcome Trust Sanger Institute with labs involved with the Cancer Genome Project that are each carrying out different areas of research involving cancer genomics, other diseases, and therapy improvements for both of the aforementioned.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-project] The Garnett group is headed by Mathew Garnett.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-project] They work to improve current cancer therapies by determining how alterations in the DNA of cells results in cancer and the implications this has involving patient responses to therapy and its potential improvement.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-project] The current research being carried out by the group includes the genomics of drug sensitivity, mapping synthetic-lethal dependencies in cancer cells, a new generation of organoid cancer models, and precision organoid models to study cancer gene function.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-project] The Jackson group is led by Steve Jackson, and their research focuses on how cells utilize DNA-damage response (DDR) to discover and mend damaged cellular DNA.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-project] The research they are conducting have large implications involving diseases that result from loss of function of the DDR system, such as cancer, neurodegenerative diseases, infertility, immunodeficiency, and premature aging.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-project] Pentao Liu leads the Liu group, which utilizes genetics, genomics, and cell biology in mice to study the role of gene functions in the development of normal cells and tissues as well as the development of various diseased cells and tissue, including cancer.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-project] The group invests a large interest in lineage choice, stem cell self-renewal, and differentiation, which would have implications in early detection, prevention, and therapy options for cancer and other genetic diseases.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-project] Ultan McDermott heads the McDermott Group.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-project] The group utilizes next-generation sequencing technologies, genetic screens, and bioinformatics to increase the knowledge of the effect that cancer genomes have on drug sensitivity and resistance in relation to patients.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-project] The different types of genetic screens being used include CRISPR, chemical mutagenesis, and RNAi.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-project] The main areas of focus by the group involve the pharmacogenomics of cancer and genetic screens to build a reserve of drug resistances in cancer.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-project] The leader of the Nik-Zainal group is Serena Nik-Zainal.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-project] The group uses computational methods to identify the unique signature of mutagenesis in somatic cells to help increase the understanding of how mutations in DNA contribute to aging and cancer.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-project] As more cancer genomes are sequenced the information the group generates will encompass a more robust collection, allowing for understanding of how mutations lead to different types and even subtypes of cancer.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-project] The Vassiliou group is led by George Vassiliou, and they focus on hematological cancer.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-project] The group studies how different genes and their pathways assist in the evolution of blood cancers, with an ultimate goal of developing treatment that will increase the quality and length of life of patients.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-project] The group utilizes single cell genome variants and its transcribed RNA to study the rate of mutation, genomic instability in gametogenesis and embryogenesis, and the effects of cellular heterogeneity on health and disease.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-project] In an attempt to better understand the mechanics of the mutations that lead to the development of cancer the Nik-Zainal group carried out a study that involved the cataloging of the somatic mutations for 21 different breast cancers.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-project] The group then utilized mathematical methods to help determine the unique mutational signatures of the underlying processes leading to the evolution from healthy to diseased tissue for each of the sampled cancers.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-project] The results showed that the mutations included several single and double nucleotide substitutions that were able to be differentiated.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-project] The unique mutations for each cancer allowed for the 21 samples to be categorized based on type and subtype of cancer, showing a relationship between mutations and the type of resulting cancer.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-project] While the group was able to identify these mutations they were unable to determine the underlying mechanisms resulting in them.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-project] The McDermott group in participation with other labs worked to find new treatment possibilities for acute myeloid leukemia (AML), an aggressive cancer with a poor prognosis.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-project] They accomplished this by designing a CRISPR genome wide screening tool to locate areas in the genome that would be more susceptible to treatment in the AML cells.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-project] The research identified 492 essential genes to the function of the AML cells that would be accessible to being therapeutic targets.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-project] The group validated the obtained results by genetic and pharmacological inhibition on select genes.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-project] Inhibition of one of the selected genes, *KAT2A,* was able to suppress the growth of the AML cells across several genotypes will leaving noncancerous cells undamaged.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-project] The results from this study propose several promising therapeutic options for AML that will need to farther investigated.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-sequencing] Unlike whole genome (WG) sequencing which is typically from blood cells, such as J.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-sequencing] Watson’s WG sequencing projects, saliva, epithelial cells or bone - cancer genome sequencing involves direct sequencing of primary tumor tissue, adjacent or distal normal tissue, the tumor micro environment such as fibroblast/stromal cells, or metastatic tumor sites.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-sequencing] Similar to whole genome sequencing, the information generated from this technique include: identification of nucleotide bases (DNA or RNA), copy number and sequence variants, mutation status, and structural changes such as chromosomal translocations and fusion genes.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-sequencing] Cancer genome sequencing is not limited to WG sequencing and can also include exome, transcriptome, micronome sequencing, and end-sequence profiling.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-sequencing] These methods can be used to quantify gene expression, miRNA expression, 3D genome organization, and identify alternative splicing events in addition to sequence data.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-sequencing] The first report of cancer genome sequencing appeared in 2006.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-sequencing] In this study 13,023 genes were sequenced in 11 breast and 11 colorectal tumors.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-sequencing] A subsequent follow up was published in 2007 where the same group added just over 5,000 more genes and almost 8,000 transcript species to complete the exomes of 11 breast and colorectal tumors.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-sequencing] The first whole cancer genome to be sequenced was from cytogenetically normal acute myeloid leukaemia by Ley *et al.* in November 2008.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-sequencing] The first breast cancer tumor was sequenced by Shah *et al.* in October 2009, the first lung and skin tumors by Pleasance *et al.* in January 2010, and the first prostate tumors by Berger *et al.* in February 2011.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-sequencing] Historically, cancer genome sequencing efforts has been divided between transcriptome-based sequencing projects and DNA-centered efforts.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-sequencing] The Cancer Genome Anatomy Project (CGAP) was first funded in 1997 with the goal of documenting the sequences of RNA transcripts in tumor cells.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-sequencing] As technology improved, the CGAP expanded its goals to include the determination of gene expression profiles of cancerous, precancerous and normal tissues.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-sequencing] The CGAP published the largest publicly available collection of cancer expressed sequence tags in 2003.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-sequencing] The Sanger Institute's Cancer Genome Project, first funded in 2005, focuses on DNA sequencing.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-sequencing] It has published a census of genes causally implicated in cancer, and a number of whole-genome resequencing screens for genes implicated in cancer.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-sequencing] The International Cancer Genome Consortium (ICGC) was founded in 2007 with the goal of integrating available genomic, transcriptomic and epigenetic data from many different research groups.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-sequencing] As of December 2011, the ICGC includes 45 committed projects and has data from 2,961 cancer genomes available.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-sequencing] The process of tumorigenesis that transforms a normal cell to a cancerous cell involve a series of complex genetic and epigenetic changes.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-sequencing] Identification and characterization of all these changes can be accomplished through various cancer genome sequencing strategies.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-sequencing] The power of cancer genome sequencing lies in the heterogeneity of cancers and patients.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-sequencing] Most cancers have a variety of subtypes and combined with these ‘cancer variants’ are the differences between a cancer subtype in one individual and in another individual.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-sequencing] Cancer genome sequencing allows clinicians and oncologists to identify the specific and unique changes a patient has undergone to develop their cancer.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-sequencing] Based on these changes, a personalized therapeutic strategy can be undertaken.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-sequencing] A big contribution to cancer death and failed cancer treatment is clonal evolution at the cytogenetic level, for example as seen in acute myeloid leukaemia (AML).
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-sequencing] In a Nature study published in 2011, Ding et al. identified cellular fractions characterized by common mutational changes to illustrate the heterogeneity of a particular tumor pre- and post-treatment vs. normal blood in one individual.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-sequencing] These cellular factions could only have been identified through cancer genome sequencing, showing the information that sequencing can yield, and the complexity and heterogeneity of a tumor within one individual.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-sequencing] Combined with these efforts, the International Cancer Genome Consortium (a larger organization) is a voluntary scientific organization that provides a forum for collaboration among the world's leading cancer and genomic researchers.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-sequencing] The Cancer Genome Projects goal is to identify sequence variants and mutations critical in the development of human cancers.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-sequencing] The project involves the systematic screening of coding genes and flanking splice junctions of all genes in the human genome for acquired mutations in human cancers.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-sequencing] To investigate these events, the discovery sample set will include DNA from primary tumor, normal tissue (from the same individuals) and cancer cell lines.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-sequencing] All results from this project are amalgamated and stored within the COSMIC cancer database.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-sequencing] COSMIC also includes mutational data published in scientific literature.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-sequencing] The TCGA is a multi-institutional effort to understand the molecular basis of cancer through genome analysis technologies, including large-scale genome sequencing techniques.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-sequencing] Hundreds of samples are being collected, sequenced and analyzed.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-sequencing] Currently the cancer tissue being collected include: central nervous system, breast, gastrointestinal, gynecologic, head and neck, hematologic, thoracic, and urologic.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-sequencing] The components of the TCGA research network include: Biospecimen Core Resources, Genome Characterization Centers, Genome Sequencing Centers, Proteome Characterization Centers, a Data Coordinating Center, and Genome Data Analysis Centers.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-sequencing] Each cancer type will undergo comprehensive genomic characterization and analysis.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-sequencing] The data and information generated is freely available through the projects TCGA data portal.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-sequencing] The ICGC’s goal is “To obtain a comprehensive description of genomic, transcriptomic and epigenomic changes in 50 different tumor types and/or subtypes which are of clinical and societal importance across the globe”.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-sequencing] Cancer genome sequencing utilizes the same technology involved in whole genome sequencing.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-sequencing] The history of sequencing has come a long way, originating in 1977 by two independent groups - Fredrick Sanger’s enzymatic didoxy DNA sequencing technique and the Allen Maxam and Walter Gilbert chemical degradation technique.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-sequencing] Following these landmark papers, over 20 years later ‘Second Generation’ high-throughput next generation sequencing (HT-NGS) was born followed by ‘Third Generation HT-NGS technology’ in 2010.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-sequencing] The figures to the right illustrate the general biological pipeline and companies involved in second and third generation HT-NGS sequencing.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-sequencing] Three major second generation platforms include Roche/454 Pyro-sequencing, ABI/SOLiD sequencing by ligation, and Illumina’s bridge amplification sequencing technology.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-sequencing] Three major third generation platforms include Pacific Biosciences Single Molecule Real Time (SMRT) sequencing, Oxford Nanopore sequencing, and Ion semiconductor sequencing.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-sequencing] As with any genome sequencing project, the reads must be assembled to form a representation of the chromosomes being sequenced.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-sequencing] With cancer genomes, this is usually done by aligning the reads to the human reference genome.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-sequencing] Since even non-cancerous cells accumulate somatic mutations, it is necessary to compare sequence of the tumor to a matched normal tissue in order to discover which mutations are unique to the cancer.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-sequencing] In some cancers, such as leukemia, it is not practical to match the cancer sample to a normal tissue, so a different non-cancerous tissue must be used.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-sequencing] It has been estimated that discovery of all somatic mutations in a tumor would require 30-fold sequencing coverage of the tumor genome and a matched normal tissue.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-sequencing] By comparison, the original draft of the human genome had approximately 65-fold coverage.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-sequencing] To facilitate further improvement in somatic mutation detection in cancer, the Sequencing Quality Control Phase 2 Consortium has established a pair of tumor-normal cell lines as community reference samples and data sets for the benchmarking of cancer mutation detections.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-sequencing] A major goal of cancer genome sequencing is to identify driver mutations: genetic changes which increase the mutation rate in the cell, leading to more rapid tumor evolution and metastasis.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-sequencing] It is difficult to determine driver mutations from DNA sequence alone; but drivers tend to be the most commonly shared mutations amongst tumors, cluster around known oncogenes, and are tend to be non-silent.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-sequencing] Passenger mutations, which are not important in the progression of the disease, are randomly distributed throughout the genome.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-sequencing] It has been estimated that the average tumor carries c.a.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-sequencing] 80 somatic mutations, fewer than 15 of which are expected to be drivers.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-sequencing] A personal-genomics analysis requires further functional characterization of the detected mutant genes, and the development of a basic model of the origin and progression of the tumor.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-sequencing] This analysis can be used to make pharmacological treatment recommendations.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-sequencing] As of February 2012, this has only been done for patients clinical trials designed to assess the personal genomics approach to cancer treatment.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-sequencing] A large-scale screen for somatic mutations in breast and colorectal tumors showed that many low-frequency mutations each make small contribution to cell survival.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-sequencing] If cell survival is determined by many mutations of small effect, it is unlikely that genome sequencing will uncover a single "Achilles heel" target for anti-cancer drugs.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-sequencing] However, somatic mutations tend to cluster in a limited number of signalling pathways, which are potential treatment targets.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-sequencing] Cancers are heterogeneous populations of cells.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-sequencing] When sequence data is derived from a whole tumor, information about the differences in sequence and expression pattern between cells is lost.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-sequencing] This difficulty can be ameliorated by single-cell analysis.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-sequencing] Clinically significant properties of tumors, including drug resistance, are sometimes caused by large-scale rearrangements of the genome, rather than single mutations.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-sequencing] In this case, information about single nucleotide variants will be of limited utility.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-sequencing] Cancer genome sequencing can be used to provide clinically relevant information in patients with rare or novel tumor types.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-sequencing] Translating sequence information into a clinical treatment plan is highly complicated, requires experts of many different fields, and is not guaranteed to lead to an effective treatment plan.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-sequencing] The *incidentalome* is the set of detected genomic variants not related to the cancer under study.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-sequencing] (The term is a play on the name incidentaloma, which designates tumors and growths detected on whole-body imaging by coincidence).
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cancer-genome-sequencing] The detection of such variants may result in additional measures such as further testing or lifestyle management.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cosmic-cancer-database] The COSMIC (Catalogue of Somatic Mutations in Cancer) database was designed to collect and display information on somatic mutations in cancer.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cosmic-cancer-database] It was launched in 2004, with data from just four genes, HRAS, KRAS2, NRAS and BRAF.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cosmic-cancer-database] These four genes are known to be somatically mutated in cancer.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cosmic-cancer-database] Since its creation, the database has expanded rapidly.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cosmic-cancer-database] By 2005 COSMIC contained 529 genes screened from 115,327 tumours, describing 20,981 mutations.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cosmic-cancer-database] By August 2009 it contained information from 1.5 million experiments performed, encompassing 13,423 genes in almost 370,000 tumours and describing over 90,000 mutations.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cosmic-cancer-database] COSMIC version 48, released in July 2010, incorporates mutation data from p53 in collaboration with the International Agency for Research on Cancer.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cosmic-cancer-database] In addition, it provided updated gene co-ordinates for the most recent human reference genome builds.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cosmic-cancer-database] This release includes data from over 2.76 million experiments on over half a million tumours.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cosmic-cancer-database] The number of mutations documented in this release totals 141,212.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cosmic-cancer-database] The website is focused on presenting complex phenotype-specific mutation data in a graphical manner.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cosmic-cancer-database] Data is taken from selected genes, initially in the Cancer Gene Census, as well as literature search from PubMed.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cosmic-cancer-database] Data can be accessed via selection of a gene or cancer tissue type (phenotype), either using *browse by* features or the *search* box.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cosmic-cancer-database] Results show summary information with mutation counts and frequencies.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cosmic-cancer-database] The gene summary page provides a mutation spectrum map and external resources; the phenotype (tissue) summary page provides lists of mutated genes.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cosmic-cancer-database] The figure shows the CDKN2A gene, which is a tumor suppressor that leads to cancer when it is inactivated.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cosmic-cancer-database] The COSMIC database contains thousands of somatic mutations that are implicated in the development of cancer.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cosmic-cancer-database] The database collects information from two major sources.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cosmic-cancer-database] Firstly, mutations in known cancer genes are collected from the literature.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cosmic-cancer-database] The list of genes that undergo manual curation are identified by their presence in the Cancer Gene Census.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cosmic-cancer-database] Secondly, data for inclusion in the database is collected from whole genome resequencing studies of cancer samples undertaken by the Cancer Genome Project.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cosmic-cancer-database] For example, Campbell and colleagues used next generation sequencing to examine samples from two individuals with lung cancer which led to the identification of 103 somatic DNA rearrangements.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cosmic-cancer-database] COSMIC also catalogues mutational signatures in human cancer through the COSMIC Signatures group, which represents a collaboration between COSMIC, the Wellcome Sanger Institute, and the University of California, San Diego.
[src:cancer-genome-sequencing/cosmic-cancer-database] The COSMIC signatures database has been leveraged to catalogue the prevalence of specific mutational signatures in human cancer, such as the frequency of ultraviolet radiation-mediated mutagenesis in skin cancers.
